Configure Authentication and TLS on Elastic Server:

Update /etc/elasticsearch/elasticsearch.yml
xpack.security.enabled: true 
xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled: true
systemctl restart elasticsearch

Set Built-in Users Password

Go to this path /usr/share/elasticsearch/bin
Run the command ./elasticsearch-setup-passwords interactive

************************************
Configure Logstash Authentication

Update the logstash's configuration file /etc/logstash/conf.d/logstash.conf
Add 2 lines on the Elasticsearch's Output plugging:
user =>'elastic'
password =>'password'
systemctl restart logstash

*use the password you keyed-in in the previous steps
*in our case is cfglog.conf as mentioned in the handbook

***********************************
Configure Filebeat Authentication

Update /etc/filebeat/filebeat.yml
Uncomment the username and password, and update the password value on the Authentication credentials
systemctl restart filebeat
*use the password you keyed-in in the previous steps

***************************************
Configure Kibana Authentication

Update /etc/kibana/kibana.yml
elasticsearch.username: “kibana_system”
elasticsearch.password: “password”
systemctl restart kibana
